# Git & PR Conventions

## Commit Messages

Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary>

<optional body explaining WHY, not WHAT>
```

**Types:** `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `ci`
**Scope:** package or area affected (e.g. `feat(ui): add toast component`)

- Subject line: imperative mood, lowercase, no period, max 72 chars
- Body: wrap at 80 chars, explain motivation and trade-offs

## Branch Naming

```
feat/<ticket-id>-short-description
fix/<ticket-id>-short-description
chore/<ticket-id>-short-description
```

## Pull Requests

- Title matches the primary commit convention: `feat(scope): description`
- Body includes: Summary (what + why), Test Plan, Breaking Changes (if any)
- One logical change per PR — avoid mixing refactors with features
- Keep PRs under 400 lines when possible; split large changes into stacked PRs

## Protected Branches

- Never force-push to `main` or `develop`
- All merges to `main` require passing CI + at least one approval
- Squash-merge feature branches; rebase for long-lived branches
